He's a viable streamer if you're in a pinch. Tonyan has a 14.3% targets share, seeing six red zone targets (11th) this season. He's finished as a TE1 twice this season. He's 34th in PFF receiving grade and 15th in yards per route run (minimum 15 targets). Tennessee is sixth in receiving yards and fifth in yards per reception allowed to tight ends.

McBride is a stash, but don't start him this week. He should take over the every down tight end role without Zach Ertz in the lineup. Last week McBride only drew one target but had an 82.1% route run rate. As a top prospect known for his receiving prowess in the draft process, McBride has Greg Dulcich-type upside down the stretch. The 49ers are 11th in DVOA against tight ends, conceding the seventh-fewest receiving yards and second-lowest yards per reception.
In Weeks 8-9, the Patriots have returned to cutting Henry's routes (47.4% route run rate) which takes him out of the fantasy streaming pool at tight end.

Thomas is a TE2. Over the last two games, he's played at least 72% of snaps (67.2% route run rate) with a 13.7% target share (3.5 targets per game) and only six receiving yards per game. The Texans have been a slightly above-average matchup for tight ends with the 11th-highest yards per reception, 13th-highest catch rate, and the tenth-most receiving touchdowns (tied).

Stoll is a deep league matchup-based desperation heave. Stoll could easily split routes and snaps with Tyree Jackson and Grant Calcaterra until Dallas Goedert is healed up. Stoll has one red zone target this season, with a 2.8% target share and 0.62 yards per route run. He's decently athletic, with an 87th percentile agility score, but his speed score is only in the 60th percentile. The Colts give up production by the bunches to tight ends, which is the only reason I'm mentioning him. Indy is 28th in DVOA against tight ends allowing the third-highest catch rate, 12th-highest yards per reception, and ninth-most receptions.
Hargrave has six sacks in his last three games and needs to be started as a DT1/DL2 option for Week 11. Keep rolling with the defensive tackle until he slows down.

Jerry Hughes continues to get it done for Texans, racking up four solos, one sack, and two tackles for loss in Week 10. He is now up to eight sacks on the season, good for a tie for sixth in the league. Hughes is up to four sacks in his last three games and is all but certain to set a new career high in sacks during his age-34 season. Treat him as an upside DL2 option for a plus Week 11 matchup against a Washington Commanders team surrendering the 14th most fantasy points per game to the defensive end position. Start Hughes in leagues of all sizes.

Leonard Williams seems to be rounding back into form and needs to be rostered in all competitive leagues. A DT1/DL2 mainstay when healthy, Williams racked up five solos, four assists, 0.5 sacks, and a forced fumble in Week 10. He has posted back-to-back five solo outings, a sign that he is ready to produce like the monster, run-stuffing defensive tackle we all know and love. He has 1.5 sacks over his last two games, but with Williams, his value comes from his tackle consistency. Start him as a DT1/DL2 option for Week 11.

Aidan Hutchinson has been impressing over the last couple of weeks, most recently piling up eight solos, one sack, and one tackle for loss. He has been as inconsistent as one would expect from a rookie but has flashed his upside on multiple occasions. He is still more DL3 than DL2 due to said inconsistency but is someone all competitive league managers will want on their roster down the stretch. Treat him as a potential DL2 option for a plus Week 11 matchup against a New York Giants team relinquishing the 10th most fantasy points per game to the defensive end position.
Simmons is a DT1/DL2 option for a plus Week 11 matchup against a Green Bay Packers team allowing the fourth most fantasy points per game to the defensive tackle position.

Justin Houston has been as hot as any pass rusher in the NFL. Through just six games, Houston sits tied for fourth in the league with 8.5 sacks. Even more impressive? Houston has 6.5 sacks in his last three contests. It was hard to recommend Houston at the start of his recent tear as he notched back-to-back two sacks games but played less than 35 percent of the snaps in both. Happily, Houston climbed up to 65 percent of the snaps before the bye, notching another 2.5 sacks. If Houston sees north of 50 percent of the snaps, he is an easy play as a DL2 or even a DL1 option (at least until he cools down). Treat him as a DL2 with DL1 upside for a plus Week 11 matchup against a Carolina Panthers team relinquishing the seventh most fantasy points per game to the outside linebacker position.

Epenesa saw his snaps skyrocket with Greg Rousseau sidelined and figures to have at least a couple more weeks of increased fantasy relevance. He was impressive with his added opportunity, racking up three solos, one sack, one tackle for loss, one forced fumble, and two passes defended. He is still part of a rotation that includes Shaq Lawson, Boogie Basham, and Von Miller, but Rousseau's absence leaves a massive snap hole to fill, and Epenesa was the biggest beneficiary in Week 10. Treat him as a DL3 for a neutral Week 11 matchup against a Cleveland Browns team allowing the 22nd most fantasy points per game to the position. Start Epenesa if you find yourself in a bye-week pinch.

Enagbare is worth a look as a DL4 option for those who may find themselves in a bye-week pinch. Kingsley started and played 75 percent of the snaps with Rashan Gary lost for the season and has the talent and opportunity to produce DL3-level numbers most weeks.
Tanoh should see an increase in snaps with both Cameron Jordan and Marcus Davenport ruled out for Week 11.  He should have enough opportunity to post DL3-level production.
Roquan is locked in as an LB1 option for Week 11 despite the neutral matchup against a Carolina Panthers team surrendering just the 22nd most fantasy points per game to the position.
Edwards is an elite option for Week 11 thanks to a plus matchup against an Indianapolis Colts team allowing the third most fantasy points per game to the linebacker position.

Mosley is locked in as a top-five option for Week 11. He has been one of the most consistent options at the position all season and seems primed for another strong outing against the New England Patriots.

Wagner has battled inconsistency as a member of the Los Angeles Rams but still projects as an LB2 option for Week 11 thanks to a plus matchup against a New Orleans Saints team allowing the fourth most fantasy points per game to the position.

Bolton has an LB1 overall upside for Week 11 thanks to a plus matchup against a Los Angeles Chargers team allowing the most fantasy points per game to the position. Start him with confidence as an IDP1.

Rashaan is locked in as an LB1 option for Week 11. He will square off against a Chicago Bears team allowing the 11th most fantasy points per game to the position, giving him a high floor for the week.

Zaire is locked in as an LB1 option for the rest of the season and looks like a top-five play for a plus Week 11 matchup against a Philadelphia Eagles team allowing the eighth most fantasy points per game to the linebacker position.
Hicks has been excellent this season and remains an LB1 option despite a tough Week 11 matchup against a Dallas Cowboys team limiting the position to the third-fewest fantasy points per game.

Kendricks has been heating up lately and retains his LB1 status for Week 11 despite a tough on-paper matchup against a Dallas Cowboys team limiting inside linebackers to the third-fewest fantasy points per game.
Okereke is a strong LB2 option for Week 11, thanks to a tasty matchup against a Philadelphia Eagles team surrendering the eighth-most fantasy points per game to the linebacker position.
Jewell has been an LB1 when healthy and is just that for a plus Week 11 matchup against a Las Vegas Raiders team surrendering the seventh most fantasy points per game to the position.

Simmons has been a strong IDP option since the Nick Vigil injury and is in the LB2 conversation for a plus Week 11 matchup against a San Francisco 49ers team allowing the sixth most fantasy points per game to the position.
Mykal is an LB2 with LB1 upside for a plus Week 11 matchup against a Chicago Bears team surrendering the 11th most fantasy points per game to the position.

Perryman is an LB1 option now that he is back to the lead linebacker role for the Raiders. It is preferable to roll him out there as a LB2, but for those in a pinch, don't hesitate to give him the LB1 tap for a plus Week 11 matchup against the Las Vegas Raiders.
Zaven is an LB2 option for a plus Week 11 matchup against a San Francisco 49ers team relinquishing the sixth most fantasy points per game to the linebacker position.

Luvu was excellent on Thursday Night Football, racking up eight solos, four assists, two sacks, and two tackles for loss. Luvu has been an elite option when healthy and should continue to produce at an LB1 level when on the field. He looks to be rounding back into his pre-injury form and needs to be rostered as such. Treat him as an LB1 option for a plus Week 11 matchup against the Baltimore Ravens.
Queen is a low-floor LB3 for Week 11 due to a neutral matchup against a Carolina Panthers team allowing the 22nd most fantasy points per game to the position.

Sanborn is heating up for the Chicago Bears, exploding for nine solos, three assists, two sacks, and two tackles for loss in Week 10. He has played nearly every snap since Roquan Smith was traded to the Baltimore Ravens and should be started in all competitive leagues as an LB2 option. He has already flashed his LB1 upside and can enter the conversation if he can string together another strong outing or two. We expected to him to start hot based on his preseason play, but he has likely exceeded everyone's expectations through two weeks of action. Start Sanborn wherever possible.

Anzalone was solid again in Week 10, this time racking up six solos, four assists, one forced fumble, and one pass defended against the Chicago Bears. Anzalone has proven LB2 upside but seems to have settled in as more of an elite LB3 option in recent weeks. Treat him as just that for a neutral Week 11 matchup against New York Giants offense allowing the 14th most fantasy points per game to opposing linebackers. Start Anzalone where needed.
Jamin is set to get yet another start with Cole Holcomb sidelined, making him a low end LB2 option for Week 11. Start him where needed.

Gay was excellent in Week 10, tallying six solos, two assists, one sack, one tackle for loss, and one pass defended. This was his best game since returning from suspension, and while his snaps have yet to reach the 92 percent he saw in Week 2, he is hovering around the 70 percent mark, which is enough for him to have LB3 value most weeks. However, when he gets an elite matchup like he had in Week 10, and like he will have in Week 11, he is an LB2 with LB1 upside. Gay will draw a Los Angeles Chargers team allowing the most fantasy points per game in Week 11, so fire him up with confidence as a top-25 option.
Ernest is an LB3 with LB2 upside for Week 11 thanks to a plus matchup against a New Orleans Saints team gifting the fourth most fantasy points per game to the position.

Kaden Elliss played 96 percent of the snaps in Week 10 and needs to be rostered universally while Pete Werner is sidelined. Elliss exploded for three solos, four assists, one sack, one tackle for loss, and one forced fumble against the Pittsburgh Steelers. He looks like he will settle in as an LB2 option when he is making spot starts and is just that for Week 11 despite a tough on-paper matchup against a Los Angeles Rams team surrendering the sixth-fewest fantasy points per game to the position. Elliss is a strong enough pass rusher to get edge snaps, so he gets a boost against the turnstile known as the Rams offensive line.

McDuffie is a LB3 with LB2 upside after a strong Week 10 showing that saw him tally eight solos and five assists. McDuffie should stay busy against the Titans ground game and has what looks like a high floor for Week 11.

Highsmith was excellent in Week 10, racking up three solos, two assists, two sacks, two tackles for loss, and one forced fumble. Tied for fourth in the league with 8.5 sacks, Highsmith has been a revelation for the Steelers and IDP managers alike. He should only get better now that T.J. Watt has returned to the lineup and projects as a high-upside DL2 option the rest of the way. For those of you still playing IDP at Yahoo for whatever reason, he is an LB only, so he loses a bit of value. Treat him as a high-end DL2 option for a plus Week 11 matchup against a Cincinnati Bengals team allowing the 16th most fantasy points per game to opposing edge rushers.

Dodson looks to be in line to make the start this week in place of the injured Tremaine Edmunds. Edmunds is dealing with groin and heel injuries and missed the first two practices of the week. Dodson played nearly every snap after Edmunds went down last week and filled in for him earlier this year, posting seven solos, four assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss in a Week 5 start. Treat him as an LB3 with LB2 upside for a neutral Week 11 matchup against the Cleveland Browns.

Cody Barton played 80 percent of snaps in Week 10, notching eight solos, one assist, one interception, and one pass defended. Barton is worth a speculative add in light of the dramatic snap increase but should be left on benches while we ascertain whether his snap count was the start of a trend or was simply a gameplan-based aberration. Barton lost his full time role back in Week 3 and has seen north of 65 percent of the snaps in just two of the seven games since. He can be productive when given the requisite snaps, however, if we can't trust the snap count, he becomes a hard player to trust outside of 16+ team leagues. Keep him benched for Week 11 despite the strong performance against the Buccaneers.
Preston Smith has been rather quiet this season and should only be viewed as a roster stash in the deepest of 11 v 11 IDP leagues. Keep him benched until he starts to heat up.
Derwin is locked in as a top-three option for a plus Week 11 matchup against a Kansas City Chiefs team surrendering the eighth-most fantasy points per game to the position.
Smith looks like a top-five option for a tasty Week 11 matchup against a Dallas Cowboys offense relinquishing the most fantasy points per game to the safety position.

CJGJ is on fire and needs to be treated as a top-tier DB1 option until he cools down. A safety with true corner ball skills, CJGJ leads the NFL in interceptions and is the DB1 overall since joining the Eagles.
Budda is in the DB1 conversation for Week 11 thanks to a plus matchup against a San Francisco 49ers team allowing the seventh most fantasy points per game to the safety position.
Talanoa remains a top-three option for Week 11 thanks to a plus matchup against a Arizona Cardinals team allowing the 11th most fantasy points per game to the safety position.
Wilson has been a revelation this season and should continue to be trotted out there as a DB1 option for Week 11.

Jackson is a DB1 option for Week 11 thanks to a plus matchup against an Atlanta Falcons team allowing the 17th most fantasy points per game to the position. Jackson has been excellent this season and projects for another strong outing against what should be a run and slot heavy attack.

Brisker remains a DB1 option for Week 11 despite the neutral matchup against an Atlanta Falcons team allowing the 17th most fantasy points per game to the position. Keep rolling with the young safety in leagues of all sizes.

Damar Hamlin was excellent in Week 10, posting eight solos, three assists, and one tackle for loss. He has been filling in admirably for Micah Hyde, providing DB1 value on the season. The DB4 overall and in fantasy points per game, Hamlin is still not among the 12 most-started defensive backs at Yahoo or Sleeper. The sample size is large enough that Hamlin needs to be treated as a DB1 week-in-and-week-out. Fire him up as just that for a plus Week 11 matchup against a Cleveland Browns team surrendering the 12th most fantasy points per game to the safety position.
Owens is a DB2 option for a neutral Week 11 matchup against a Washington Commanders team allowing the 22nd most fantasy points per game to the position.
Pitre remains an elite option for Week 11 despite the neutral matchup against a Washington Commanders team surrendering just the 22nd most fantasy points to the position.
Jalen is a DB2 with DB1 upside for a Week 11 thanks to a plus matchup against a San Francisco 49ers team surrendering the seventh most fantasy points per game to the safety position.

Chinn should return to action within the next week or two, so if you happen to play in a league where he was dropped by an impatient manager, make the add immediately. Chinn is locked in as a DB1 option when healthy and should be rostered and stashed in leagues of all sizes. Treat him as a DB1 for Week 11 if active.

Grant Delpit was solid in Week 10, posting six solos and four assists in a plus matchup against the Miami Dolphins. Delpit has been a little inconsistent in his first season as a starter but has established himself as a strong DB2 option that has matchup-based DB1 upside. He will be a DB2 option for a neutral Week 11 matchup against a Buffalo Bills team allowing the 21st most fantasy points per game to the position. Start him where needed.
DeShon has been battling injuries since taking over as starter for the injured Tracy Walker but has been excellent when on the field. Fire him up as a top-five option if active for Week 11.

Kerby Joseph has been balling for the Detroit Lions, most recently posting five solos and two assists in Week 10. He has recorded at least five solos in each of his last three contests, and as his two interception Week 9 proved, he has DB1 upside when everything is clicking. Kerby gets a tough Week 11 matchup, which makes him more of a low-end DB2 option, as the New York Giants have allowed the ninth fewest fantasy points per game to the position. Start Kerby where needed.

Adderley is a DB2 option for a plus Week 11 matchup against a Kansas City Chiefs team allowing the eighth most fantasy points per game to the safety position. Nasir has battled consistency this season but has a high floor due to matchup.

Forrest played every snap in Week 10 despite Kamren Curl and Bobby McCain doing the same. The Commanders opted to utilize McCain in more slot coverage, which allowed them to play both Curl and Forrest at the same time. Forrest responded by posting three solos, three assists, one interception, one pass defended, and one fumble recovery. McCain is more suited for high-level slot play than practice squader Danny Johnson, so this is a package that the Commanders may lean on going forward. Forrest is not without some risk for Week 11 but was still seeing roughly 60 percent of the snaps in the previous few weeks, making him someone for those in a bye-week crunch to lean on. Treat him as a low-floor DB3 option for a neutral Week 11 matchup against a Houston Texans team allowing the 19th most fantasy points per game to the position.
Abram played zero defensive snaps in Week 10 and should be glued to benches until he is active for more than just special teams.

Adams was at it again in Week 10, racking up six solos, one assist, and one tackle for loss. He has been excellent as a spot starter for the Titans this season and should continue to produce when called upon. Adams has at least six solos in each of his last three starts and looks to be in line for another strong outing in Week 11 against a Green Bay Packers team allowing the second most fantasy points per game to the safety position. Plug him in where possible with an eye on rolling him out there as a DB2 option.
Stone has at least two more weeks of DB2 value before fantasy managers will have to start worrying about the return of Marcus Williams. Start him with confidence as a low-end DB2 option for Week 11.

Nick Scott went off in Week 10, racking up eight solos and one assist. The production, however, seems like an aberration and is not something to chase, regardless of your bye-week situation. This was his best fantasy output of the season and marked only the second time in nine games that he saw more than four solos. He is worth a deep league roster spot due to his every snap role but is not someone you want plugged into your lineups, even in the most desperate of situations. Keep him glued to the pine for a tough Week 11 matchup against a New Orleans team limiting the position to the third-fewest fantasy points per game.
Kazee looks to be in line to make another start for the Steelers. Minkah Fitzpatrick is at least a week or two away, giving Kazee short-term DB3 upside.

Pinnock went off in Week 10, recording three solos, one assist, 1.5 sacks, and one tackle for loss. However, this was the first time all season that Pinnock saw more than one defensive snap, so he is not someone to trust for Week 11. Yes, it is perfectly possible that Pinnock has earned himself a role going forward but until we see it, Pinnock belongs on waiver wire in all but the deepest of 11 vs 11 IDP leagues. Look elsewhere for Week 11 cover.
Jaquan has been supplanted by Cam Lewis as Jordan Poyer's top backup and as a result is no longer fantasy relevant, even when Poyer is sidelined.
